<br>
Anyway I think Christopher Hart doesn't suck. He's mediocre at best compared to other tutorial artists.<br>
His books stand a head and shoulders above those 3 step character tutorials that teach you to copy and stifle your own originality.<br>
I'd rather his vague instructions than those pieces of crap that say... 'put a line here, ok... now put a curved line here.' and give you the instruction on how to make something look exactly like what's on the page.<br>
I supppose most of the redeeming stuff in the Manga Mania book (at least for me anyway) is the fantasy art section. That personally helped me alot with my own stuff. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/utaerx.showPublicProfile?language=EN>TaerX</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/2/02 1:51:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3917.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Christopher Hart</span><hr size=1> Mr. Hart is a prolific source of &quot;How to Draw&quot; books on a variety of topics.  He and his contributing artists generally provide a cursory overview of the title topic.  I suspect he takes some pains to become familiar with that topic, but given the breadth of his work and the three of his books I purchased, I don't think he will live and breathe them to the satisfaction of any otaku or fanboy (or -girl).<br>
<br>
His books are generally visually pleasing and cover a wide range of sub-genres and sub-styles of the title topic.  I don't recall ever reading that he claims to cover the whole of any field.  He does give some very concrete examples for specific situations, but his level of detail is very spotty - some areas (usually visually striking poses or dynamic composition) will receive stroke-by-stroke detail, while others (general composition and layout, for example) is covered by a few paragraphs as if an afterthought.<br>
<br>
His Anime and Manga Mania books waste some paper in the back with supposed &quot;how to survive in Japan&quot; data that is again too sketchy to be single-source useful, and to specific for certain situations to be generally useful.<br>
<br>
I categorize them as &quot;coffee table books.&quot;  I would imagine they're good for when you show a friend a picture, and they say, &quot;Why are the eyes so big?&quot; or &quot;Oh, that's from <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Pokemon</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->, right?&quot; I would then point them at the books as a general primer for what I'm doing.  In conclusion, I think they're light enough reading (or text-optional) to give a beginner some general orientation, but they're not really useful for someone who has the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> How to Draw Manga</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> compilations or the <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Manga and Game Characters</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> books.  Given that each book in any of the three series costs $20 USD, I'd rather buy the latter two than more Hart work. <p><hr noshade size=1><center><font size=1><a href="http://www.freewebs.com/taerx/"> My FreeWebs Home Page</a> (Not a lot there)</font></center></p><i></i></td></tr></table><br><font color=#336699>- </font><a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs>Polykarbon BBS</a><font color=#336699> - </font><a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2>Photoshop and Art questions</a> <font color=#336699> - </font><a href="http://www.polykarbon.com">Polykarbon: Manga & Photoshop</a><font color=#336699> - </font><br><br><table border=0 align=center><tr><td align=center></td><td><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/image/spacer.gif" width=15 height=1 border=0></td><td align=center></td></tr></table><CENTER><!-- START BOTTOM ARTS AD SCRIPT -->
